@node Usage
===============================
 Usage
===============================

PalmDoc is, hopefully, easy to use. When running, PalmDoc will show
a window with several buttons, checkboxes and string gadgets:


Title:

This stores the title of the DOC file. It defaults to 'Untitled',
which isn't particularly meaningful. Unless you're in an absolute
hurry, it's best to type a more useful title here which will be used
by your Palm's DOC reader. DOC titles can be no more than 31
characters long - PalmDoc will stop you from entering any more than
that.


In file:

You can specify the source text filename in three ways:

First, you can type the full path and filename in the string gadget.
Note an appropriate Out File filename will be automatically generated
when you hit return or tab after typing.

Secondly, you can click the button marked "In File" alongside the
string gadget, which will bring up a file requester. Again, this
automatically creates an appropriate Out File name.

Thirdly, drag the icon of the desired source file over the PalmDoc
window and drop it onto the window - PalmDoc will set the In File and
Out File automatically.


Compression:

Tick this box if you want your DOC to be saved in a compressed format.
This is recommended. It is ticked by default.


Private:

Tick this box if you want your DOC's Private flag set. I've never used
this option, and for most DOCs it's not needed, so it defaults to
being unchecked.


Make DOC:

When you're ready to create your DOC file, click this button and
Makedoc will be passed the appropriate parameters to create the DOC
file.

Don't worry if you forget to specify a source, PalmDoc will warn you
and give you a file requester to specify the source file, and generate
an output filename automatically. You can click Cancel on the warning
or file requester to cancel the operation and return back to the main
window.



